definition.value: A drug used for its effects on the gastrointestinal system, e.g. controlling gastric acidity, regulating gastrointestinal motility and water flow, and improving digestion.
A class of anticoagulants which act by inhibiting the action of vitamin K.
An antagonist at the neurokinin-1 receptor.
An antagonist at the substance P receptor.
A drug or agent applied to the skin to control seborrhea or seborrheic dermatitis.
Any inhibitor of an acid--amino-acid ligase (EC 6.3.2.*).
An inhibitor of any metalloendopeptidase (EC 3.4.24.*).
Any substance that stimulates an immune response in the body, such as through antibody production or by presentation to a T-cell receptor after binding to a major histocompability complex (MHC).
A substance used as an indicator  of a biological state.
Any substance capable of eliciting an immune response only when attached to a large carrier such as a protein. Examples include dinitrophenols; oligosaccharides; peptides; and heavy metals.
A chemical substance which inhibits the function of gonadotrophin-releasing hormone (GnRH).
Any inhibitor of a serine endopeptidase (EC 3.4.21.*).
A compound that exhibits agonist activity at the kappa-opioid receptor.
A compound that exhibits antagonist activity at the delta-opioid receptor.
Any inhibitor of squalene monooxygenase (EC 1.14.99.7).
Any inhibitor of an aromatic-L-amino-acid decarboxylase (EC 4.1.1.28).
Any enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of a dipeptidase (EC 3.4.13.*).
Any substance that inhibits the synthesis of DNA.
Any antigen that is a phosphorylated microbial metabolite which activates an immune response in humans.
Any compound that inhibits the action of serine palmitoyltransferase (EC 2.3.1.50).
Any compound that inhibits the action of chitin synthase (EC 2.4.1.16).
Any drug which blocks vasopressin receptors.
A drug, usually applied topically, that relieves pruritus (itching).
Any drug which binds to vasopressin receptors and triggers a response.
A reagent that forms a bond to its reaction partner (the nucleophile) by accepting both bonding electrons from that reaction partner.
A reagent that forms a bond to its reaction partner (the electrophile) by donating both bonding electrons.
A reagent used to improve selectivity in chromatographic analyses or separations, e.g. by formation of a derivative or by modification of the mobile phase.
A surfactant molecule with hydrophilic groups at both ends of a hydrophobic hydrocarbon chain
A synthetic progestogen.
A drug used for the treatment of hyperplasia (increaced cell production within an organ or tissue).
Any drug used to depigment skin, normally by decreasing the excretion of melanin from melanocytes.

A drug which interferes with the binding, fusion and entry of an HIV virion to a human cell. By blocking this step in HIV's replication cycle, such agents slow the progression from HIV infection to AIDS.
An entity which inhibits the activity of reverse transcriptase, a viral DNA polymerase enzyme that retroviruses need to reproduce.
A surfactant molecule possessing both hydrophilic and lipophilic properties.
Any inhibitor of tyrosinase (monophenol monooxygenase) (EC 1.14.18.1), an enzyme that catalyses the oxidation of phenols (such as tyrosine) and is widespread in plants and animals.
Any acid anhydride hydrolase inhibitor that inhibits the action of Ca(2+)-transporting ATPase (EC 3.6.3.8).

Any macromolecule whose structure mimics that of an epitope. When applied to immunisation, a mimotope induces the desired antibody specificities exclusively based on the principle of molecular mimicry.
Any inhibitor of a peptidase.
Any compound that inhibits the activity of a glutaminase and thus the generation of glutamate from glutamine
Any hormone produced by the thyroid gland
A class of fungicides whose members contain both a spiroketal moiety and an amino group.
Any member of the class of herbicides whose members contain a phenoxy or substituted phenoxy group.
Phenoxy herbicides whose members contain a (substituted) phenoxyacetic acid substructure, including salts and esters of (substituted) phenoxyacetic acid.
A member of a class of fungicides that contains an imidazole or triazole moiety.
Any agent that acts on an opioid receptor or affects the life cycle of an opioid  transmitter.
Any agent that acts on a mu-opioid receptor.
Any member of the class of fungicides which contain an amide group.
Any agent that acts on a delta-opioid receptor.
Any agent that acts on a kappa-opioid receptor.
An agent that binds to but does not activate an opioid receptor thereby blocking the actions of endogenous or exogenous opioid receptor agonists.
